column1: Age-standardized death rate in Austria by calendar week (excl. abroad) from 2000
column2: -) Important note Data of weekly deaths for 2000 to 2019 are final; for 2020, data are still preliminary. Deaths of Austrian residents abroad are not included in the data of any published year. Age standardized death rates are based upon the European Standard Population 2013 (European Commission (2013): “Revision of the European Standard Population – Report of Eurostat’s task force Luxembourg”. Publications Office of the European Union 2013. DOI: 10.2785/11470). For the age standardized death rates, crude deaths rates of the observed age group (deaths / population) are multiplied with the proportion of the population of the same age group according to the European Standard population. Please note that the sum of all 52 or 53 weeks in a given year does not equal the total number of deaths / death rates of the respective calendar year. In cases where January 1st is a Tuesday, Wednesday or Thursday, the first calendar week also includes the remaining days of the last calendar week of the previous year. Likewise, if the 31st of December is a Thursday, Friday or Saturday, the last calendar week also includes the first day(s) of the successive year. .) Origin of data and legal foundations Statistics Austria processes all deaths delivered by the Civil Registry Offices. Within the publication deadline not all deaths are available, yet. The age-standardized death rates published here only include calendar weeks in which the deaths were almost completely reported to Statistics Austria. .) Update Preliminary data for 2020 will be updated weekly during the ongoing Corona crisis. Every week, deaths for a new week will be published; at the same time, results for previous weeks will be updated (revised). .) Please note that the sum of all 52 or 53 weeks in a given year does not equal the total number of deaths of the respective calendar year. In cases where January 1st is a Tuesday, Wednesday or Thursday, the first calendar week also includes the remaining days of the last calendar week of the previous year. Likewise, if the 31st of December is a Thursday, Friday or Saturday, the last calendar week also includes the first day(s) of the successive year.

NUTS is the abbreviation of 'Nomenclature des unites territoriales statistiques', in English 'Classification of territorial units for statistics' and is a general, hierarchically structured territorial classification of EU member states. Parameters bear - in brackets - a three- to multi-digit code depending on the respective level; the first two digits are 'AT', which is the ISO (International Standards Organisation) 2 digit for Austria.
